Here's the recommended approach using a custom `Window` subclass with `Preferences` for fast state persistence:

**1. Create a ViewModel for your notes page:**

```csharp
// ViewModels/NoteViewModel.cs
public class NoteViewModel : INotifyPropertyChanged
{
    private string _draftText = string.Empty;

    public string DraftText
    {
        get => _draftText;
        set { _draftText = value; PropertyChanged?.Invoke(this, new(nameof(DraftText))); }
    }

    public event PropertyChangedEventHandler? PropertyChanged;
}
```

**2. Create a custom Window subclass that saves/restores state:**

```csharp
// AppWindow.cs
public class AppWindow : Window
{
    private readonly NoteViewModel _viewModel;

    public AppWindow(Page page, NoteViewModel viewModel) : base(page)
    {
        _viewModel = viewModel;
    }

    protected override void OnStopped()
    {
        base.OnStopped();
        Preferences.Set("draft_text", _viewModel.DraftText);
    }

    protected override void OnResumed()
    {
        base.OnResumed();
        _viewModel.DraftText = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
    }

    protected override void OnDestroying()
    {
        base.OnDestroying();
        // Android back-button can skip Stopped, so save here too
        Preferences.Set("draft_text", _viewModel.DraftText);
    }
}
```

**3. Wire it up in `App.xaml.cs`:**

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    private readonly NoteViewModel _viewModel = new();

    public App()
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        // Restore any previously saved draft on launch
        _viewModel.DraftText = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
    }

    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
    {
        var page = new NotePage { BindingContext = _viewModel };
        return new AppWindow(page, _viewModel);
    }
}
```

**4. Bind the Editor in your XAML:**

```xml
<!-- NotePage.xaml -->
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             x:Class="YourApp.NotePage"
             x:DataType="vm:NoteViewModel">
    <Editor Text="{Binding DraftText}" Placeholder="Start typing..." />
</ContentPage>
```

### Key points

| Event | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `OnStopped` | App backgrounded — save draft via `Preferences` |
| `OnResumed` | App foregrounded — restore draft |
| `OnDestroying` | Also save here — Android back-button can skip `Stopped` |

### Pitfalls to avoid
- **Don't save in `OnDeactivated`** — it fires for dialogs/split-screen, not just backgrounding.
- **Keep handlers fast** (< 2s) — use `Preferences` for small text, not database writes.
- **`OnResumed` doesn't fire on first launch** — that's why we restore in the `App` constructor too.
